From Oblique Strategies: Faced with a choice, do both

Take a week or two, and cut the games and net.
My technique for writing 2000-7000 words a day is simple, nor requires great inspiration.
Write 100-500 words. Stop while you're crisp and still motivated. Go do something else useful. Come back in 15-30 minutes, then repeat.
The idea is to never get in a miniature writer's block. When you sit down and start for the day, something of what needs to happen should be in your head.
Example: tonight, I have two tasks. One, to show how two kids misbehave but each in their own ways. Two, show the mid-point of a "there's no one else, and I don't want to be alone" romance, the kind where the kids are somewhere else for the night and the adults get to set responsibility aside.
